Q10. What are some common measures of central tendency and variability used in statistics? Explain how each measure can be used to describe a dataset.

In statistics, measures of central tendency and variability are used to summarize and describe datasets. They provide essential insights into the typical values and the spread of data points within a dataset. Here are some common measures of central tendency and variability:
I)	Measures of Central Tendency: 
a. Mean: The mean is the most common measure of central tendency. It is calculated by summing all the data points and then dividing by the number of data points. The mean represents the average value of the dataset and is sensitive to extreme values or outliers. It is suitable for datasets with a symmetric distribution.

b. Median: The median is the middle value of a dataset when it is sorted in ascending or descending order. If there is an even number of data points, the median is the average of the two middle values. The median is less affected by extreme values than the mean and is appropriate for datasets with skewed distributions or when there are outliers.

d.	Mode: The mode represents the most frequently occurring value in the dataset. A dataset can have one mode (unimodal), two modes (bimodal), or more (multimodal). The mode is useful for categorical or discrete datasets, and it can also be used to describe the peak or most common values in a continuous dataset.

II)	Measures of Variability:
a. Range: The range is the simplest measure of variability and is calculated by subtracting the minimum value from the maximum value in the dataset. It provides an understanding of the spread of the entire dataset. However, the range is sensitive to outliers and may not be the most robust measure of variability.

b. Variance: Variance is the average of the squared differences between each data point and the mean. It measures the spread of data points around the mean. Larger variance indicates greater dispersion. However, variance is influenced by the units of measurement and may not be easily interpretable.

c. Standard Deviation: The standard deviation is the square root of the variance. It provides a more interpretable measure of spread, as it is in the same units as the original data. The standard deviation is widely used because it is easy to understand and gives a sense of how much individual data points deviate from the mean.

d. Interquartile Range (IQR): The IQR is the range between the third quartile (Q3) and the first quartile (Q1) of the dataset. It provides a measure of spread that is less sensitive to extreme values or outliers compared to the range. It is useful for describing the central 50% of the data.

These measures are essential tools for summarizing and understanding datasets in statistics, helping researchers and analysts gain insights into the central tendencies and variabilities of their data.

